        "theory": {
            "id": "theory",
            "title": "Theory",
            "isApplicable": true,
            "content": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "A decoder is a combinational circuit that converts a binary code at its inputs into a unique output line. It activates exactly one output for each possible input combination, with all other outputs remaining inactive. A decoder with n input lines has a maximum of 2^n output lines, though some decoders may have fewer outputs — in such cases at least one output pattern will be repeated."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "A 3:8 decoder has 3 input lines (I0, I1, I2) and 8 output lines (Y0–Y7). For each of the 8 possible 3-bit input combinations, exactly one output line is set high while all others remain low. The active output corresponds to the decimal value of the 3-bit binary input."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "In Verilog, I and Y are represented as bit-vectors (buses). The case statement assigns a unique one-hot output to Y for every input combination, with exactly one bit of Y set to 1 in each assignment."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The truth table for the 3:8 decoder is given below:"
                },
                {
